Suppose one finds that a 36\,N force compresses a particular spring by 6.0\,cm.
A block with a mass of 2.0\,kg rests on a frictionless surface and is attached
to this spring.
The other end of the spring is rigidly fixed (see Fig.\,6).
The block is compressed 5.0\,cm from its equilibrium position.
What work does the spring do in pushing the block back to its equilibrium
position?

\fullwidthfigure{240pt}{Fig.\,6. Force characteristics of a spring.
(a) The spring force F as a function of its displacement x.
(b) The spring in its equilibrium state.
(c) The spring stretched by a displacement x to the right and with a spring
force F to the left.
(d) The spring compressed with a displacement x to the spring force F to the
right.}

The value of the spring constant is:
\begin{displaymath}
k = -\dfrac{F}{x} = \dfrac{-36\unit{N}}{-6.0 \times 10^{-2}\unit{m}} =
6.0 \times 10^2\,{\rm N/m}.
\end{displaymath}
Then the work done by the spring on the block is:
\begin{displaymath}
W = \int \vec{F}_R \cdot d\vec{s} = \int_{-x}^0 (-k x)\,dx,
\end{displaymath}
since \vect{F} is parallel to \m{d\vec{s}} and is in the same direction.
Thus:
\begin{displaymath}
W = - k \int_{-x}^0 x\,dx = \dfrac{k x^2}{2} = 0.75J.
\end{displaymath}
We can arrive at the same result graphically by calculating the area under
the ``\m{F} versus \m{x}'' curve.
Since the area of a triangle is half its height times its base, we have:
\begin{displaymath}
\dfrac{1}{2}(-k x)(-x) = \dfrac{1}{2}k x^2.
\end{displaymath}

