\pcap{3d. Total Work. }
The most general definition of total work, expressed in line integral
formulation, is
\begin{equation}\setcounter{equation}{8}
W_{T,A\rightarrow B} = \int_A^B \vec{F}_R \cdot d\vec{s}\;{\rm where}\;
\vec{F}_R = \sum_{i=1}^N \vec{F}_i(s).
\end{equation}

Here \m{W_{T,A\rightarrow B}} is the total work done on a particle when it is
displaced from position \m{A} to position \m{B} by the force \m{\vec{F}_R}, the
resultant of all \m{N} forces acting on the particle.

